descript.abstract: This feature class contains pest and fire mortality mapped during 2016 Californian surveys. Includes estimates of trees per acre and number of trees affected, tree species affected, damage type, and damage causing agents when available. Data collected in or near California by USFS Regions 4 and 6 are also included. Detailed methods, standards and guidelines are available at the Forest Health Technology Enterprise Team website: http://www.fs.fed.us/foresthealth/technology/ads_standards.shtml
descript.purpose: Map tree mortality and other forest damage in California during the year 2016. Suitable for regional applications only (1:100,000 scale or smaller). The end user of this data should be advised that the aerial detection surveys were undertaken in single-engine high-wing aircraft flying 1,000 - 2,000' above ground level, sometimes in hazy or turbulent conditions. Since surveyors visually scan areas up to two miles in either direction of the aircraft, mortality on the opposing side of ridges or peaks may be obscured. Due to these data collection limitations polygon boundaries may not be exact representations of features found on the ground. Caution is advised when attempting to overlay ADS data with other raster or aerial photography features. See Use Constraints for more information.
descript.supplinf: The USFS Region 5 aerial detection survey was undertaken by Forest Health Protection and other Forest Service personnel and National Park Service personnel. The surveys began in 1993 and have been conducted annually through 2016. Surveys conducted in 1978 are also included. Since 2001 surveys were completed for all forested areas in R5 National Forests, and also included National Parks (Lassen, Sequoia-Kings and Yosemite), other Federal, Tribal, State and private lands in or near National Forest boundaries. Polygons and their attributes were estimated visually by trained surveyors according to Forest Health Protection standards. Digital aerial sketchmapping (DASM) sytems were used for the entire survey starting in 2006. Previous years were conducted with a combination of DASM and paper maps. Surveys were undertaken in single-engine high-wing aircraft flying 1,000 - 2,000' above ground level, sometimes in hazy or turbulent conditions. Mapped damage included both biotic (insect, disease, and vertebrate damage) and abiotic agents (wind, geothermal and wild and prescribed fire damage). â€¢ Due to the rapid progression of mortality and difficulties in separating 2015 from 2016 mortality ocular estimates, areas where mortality polygons overlap between the 2015 and 2016 surveys have been adjusted to reduce duplicative mortality. In areas where the 2016 trees per acres (TPA) was greater than 2015, the 2015 TPA was subtracted from the 2016 TPA. In areas where the 2015 TPA was greater than 2016, the 2016 TPA was retained. This also has the possibility to produce a 0 trees per acre, if the 2015 and 2016 TPA are the same value. 2015 Survey TPA 2016 Survey TPA Result 10 50 40 50 10 10 50 50 0

Because the damage agents are mapped from the air, exact identification of the specific tree host, insect, disease and/or damage causal agent cannot be guaranteed. Completeness is variable. The intent is to survey all forested lands in California, but in any given year, this may not happen for various reasons (weather, fires, funding, etc.). Users must exercise caution regarding the spatial accuracy of these data due to the subjective nature of aerial sketch mapping time constraints and the scale of data collection.

edom.edomvds: Damage that results in physical or functional removal of foliage, partially or wholly by some agent. A list of agents causing defoliation will be developed regionally from the Field Sampled Vegetation (FSVeg) VEG_DISTURBANCE_AGENTS code list, to be included as part
Standing dead trees that have died since the last survey

Foliage is a color other than green, such as yellow, red, purple, black, or brown. If it is known that the discoloration will result in defoliation or mortality within 1 or 2 years, then it can be coded as defoliation or mortality rather than discoloration, e.g. bark beetle-killed trees fading from green to yellow to red before dying. A list of agents causing discoloration will be developed regionally from the FSVeg code list, to be included as part of the definition.

Distal portions (tips) of branches in upper part of crown killed since last survey, with dead or dying (yellow, red, or brown) foliage. Non-distal portions of these branches have visible green, live foliage. A list of agents causing dieback will be developed regionally from the FSVeg code list, to be included as part of the definition.

Top portion of the tree, including the terminal and all branches in that area, killed since the last survey with dead or dying foliage visible (yellow, red, or brown). Stem is not broken. This type of damage is usually associated with conifers; it can, however, be seen in hardwoods that have a distinctive main stem and terminal. A list of agents causing top kill will be developed regionally from the FSVeg code list, to be included as part of the definition.

Broken branches in any portion of the crown since the last survey or that has occurred recently. Broken branches identified by either a missing or a dangling distal portion; exposed wood at break is bright white or light colored (exposed wood on breaks older than one year has usually darkened). Non-distal portions of these branches have visible green, live foliage.

Main stem broken at any point or uprooted since last survey or that has occurred recently. Tree is no longer vertical above break or uprooting. Trees that have been recently uprooted or broken have green or fading foliage and exposed wood at break is bright white or light colored (exposed wood in breaks older than one year has usually darkened).
Some, but not all, branches on tree with red or yellow (dying) foliage since last survey. Remaining branches green.
A type of damage other than described in the categories above.
